> I have got procmail to work fine, no problems.  But I have noticed
> some people are using  :0:  in their rc files, versus  :0.
> 
> Whats the difference?

A ':' at the end of the recipe flag line specifies that procmail
should use a lockfile during that recipe's processing.
Recipes with just :0 do not use a lockfile during recipe processing.
A 3rd form of the flag line is :0:lockfile which tells procmail
to use "lockfile" as the name of the lockfile.

Use of lockfiles is recommended for all recipes that result
in writing to a file such as the recipes like:
:0:
*^header: whatever
folder



